Q1:
Informed Consent for Participation in Research Activities


Project Title: Priority Queues and Decision-Making

Principal Investigator: Colin Camerer; Address: MC228-77, California Institute of Technology, Pasadena, CA 91125;
Phone: 626-395-4054; Email: camerer@hss.caltech.edu

Purpose of this Research Study: The purpose of this study is research. This is not a clinical study and we do not provide medical treatment. This study is about understanding how people decide what tasks to do first, especially when they have limited time. While we are happy to talk to you more about the scientific findings of our work, we will not give you any feedback. This means we cannot tell you how you compare to other people on any measures. If you have any questions about any part of the study or this informed consent, please ask the researcher. Questions are encouraged.

Background: This project aims to understand how productivity, efficiency and task ability vary when a trivia task is presented to large groups. Our goal is to identify which questions in the following trivia task are neutral and and to discard any questions which are not independent and uncorrelated to individual characteristics.

Who Can Participate: Any person over 18 years of age residing in the US is eligible to participate.

What Will Be Done: In this survey, you will answer some questions about how you are currently feelings. Next, you will play a game where you run an ice cream shop. During this game, we will record where you are looking on the screen with an eyetracker done with your webcam. NO images (including face images) will be recorded; only the screen coordinates of where you looked will be recorded. There will be different ice cream orders to fill, and each one will give you a certain amount of points. As more orders come in, you will need to decide which orders to do first. Some orders are harder than others. You will click on the ice cream order you want to do, then click on the icons on the screen for that order. At the end of the game, you will answer more questions about how you currently feel, what you thought of the game, and some basic information (age, gender, race, etc.).

Possible Risks and Discomforts: The risks or discomforts to you as a result of participating in the study are minimal. The testing may result in mild fatigue, boredom, and or frustration with the survey. These risks are no more than might be expected when performing any other psychological survey.



Collaborative Study/Sharing Research Data


Possible Benefits: You personally will not benefit directly from participation in this research study in any way. This research may help extend our understanding of how people perceive others.

Alternatives: Your alternative is to choose not to participate in this study.

Compensation: You are entitled to compensation for participating in this experiment. Your compensation will be $1.00 for participation plus an extra 5¢ for every point in the game. The total possible reward is up to $5.00.

Withdrawal from Study: Your participation is voluntary. If you first agree to participate and then you change your mind, you are free to withdraw your consent and discontinue your participation in this study at any time. Your decision will not affect your relationship, if any, with Caltech and you will not be penalized or lose any benefits to which you would otherwise be entitled. To withdraw from the study, you only need to let the experimenter know. You will not be asked to explain your reasons. Subjects can withdraw and any point during the experiment. They will be paid in full and their data will be destroyed. We may also withdraw you from the study without your consent for scientific or technical reasons. We will not be able to give you detailed explanations of the reasons. 
Confidentiality of Records: Any information from this study in which you might be identified will be confidential. By signing this form, however, you allow the study investigators to make your records available to the Caltech Institutional Review Board Office and regulatory or funding agencies as required by law. If the information generated by this study is published, you will never be identified by name. Data collected from this study will be kept in Colin Camerer’s laboratory at the California Institute of Technology. We will take reasonable steps to ensure that no unauthorized person will have access to the data generated by this study. Digital data will be password protected.

Offer to Answer Questions and Research Injury Notification: The Caltech researchers have offered to answer any and all questions regarding your participation in this research study. If you have any further questions or in the event of a research-related injury, you can contact the principal investigator at 626-395-2856 (Marcos Gallo), or the Caltech Institutional Review Board Administrator at (626)395-4699 or at irb@caltech.edu. 
Voluntary Participation with Right of Refusal: You have been informed that your participation in this research study is voluntary. You are free to withdraw your consent for participation in any part of this study without any penalty.

IRB Review and Impartial Third Party: This study has been reviewed and approved by the Institutional Review Board (IRB) of the California Institute of Technology. A representative of that board, from the IRB Office, is available to discuss the review process or your rights as a research subject. The telephone number of the IRB office is 626-3954699 and their email is irb@caltech.edu.
